'''Dennis J. Trewin''' was the [[Australian Statistician]], the head of the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]], between July 2000 and January 2007.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/mining-boom-fails-to-deliver/2006/09/01/1156817098307.html | title = Mining boom fails to deliver | work = [[The Age]] | author = Tim Colebatch | date = 2006-09-02 | accessdate = 2007-01-31 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abs.gov.au/websitedbs/D3110129.NSF/f128006d2d1e7c10ca2566fd0081ba4b/abbe75f1a0d205feca25722c001003ca!OpenDocument#AUSTRALIAN%20STATISTICIAN%20DENNIS%20TR | title = Statistical News Tasmania: Australian Statistician Dennis Trewin Retires |date=November 2006 | work = Newsletter, [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] | accessdate = 2007-01-31}}</ref>

Trewin joined the ABS in 1966 as a Statistics cadet.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://abs.gov.au/websitedbs/d3310114.nsf/4a256353001af3ed4b2562bb00121564/a0209509ae816da9ca25718c000c7adf!OpenDocument | title = Senior Staff Biographies - Dennis Trewin, Australian Statistician | work = [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] | accessdate = 2007-01-31 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110727121531/http://abs.gov.au/websitedbs/d3310114.nsf/4a256353001af3ed4b2562bb00121564/a0209509ae816da9ca25718c000c7adf!OpenDocument |archivedate=27 July 2011}}</ref>  Between 1992 and 1995 he was the Deputy Government Statistician in [[Statistics New Zealand]] <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.obs-pascal.com/docs.php?doc=53 | title = Biography for Dennis Trewin | work = Observatory Pascal | year = 2004 | accessdate = 2007-01-31 }}</ref> and a Deputy Australian Statistician from 1995 to 2000, when he was appointed as the Australian Statistician.<ref name="oecd">{{cite web | url = http://www.oecd.org/speaker/0,2879,en_21571361_31834434_33630521_1_1_1_1,00.html | title = Speaker profile: Dennis Trewin | work = [[OECD]] |date=November 2004 | accessdate = 2006-06-25 }}</ref>

Dennis Trewin was the driving force behind the ABS's pioneering 'Measures of Australia's Progress' (MAP), a new system of integrated national progress measurement, linking economic, social, environmental and governance dimensions of progress, a project which gained wide respect among other national statistical offices and helped bring about the OECD's Global Project, 'Measuring the Progress of Societies'.

He holds other senior appointments in Australia such as non-judicial member of the [[Australian Electoral Commission]] and an Adjunct Professor at [[Swinburne University]].  He has held the office of President of the [[Statistical Society of Australia]].<ref name="oecd"/>

Internationally, in 2005 he completed a term as President of the [[International Statistical Institute]] having previously been Vice-President and President of the [[International Association of Survey Statisticians]].  He is a past editor of the [[International Statistical Review]].<ref name="oecd"/> He is Chairman of the Global Executive Board at the [[World Bank]], Chairman of the Asia/Pacific Committee of Statistics, and Chairman of the Advisory Board of Swinburne University of Technology's [[Swinburne Institute for Social Research]].<ref name="oecd"/>

Trewin holds honorary life memberships of the International Statistical Institute and the Statistical Society of Australia.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://demography.anu.edu.au/Seminars&Lectures/ASEP_lectures_pdf/Trewin.pdf | title = The Australian & The Scanlon Foundation presenter profile: Dennis Trewin | work = College of Arts & Social Sciences, [[Australian National University]] | accessdate = 2007-01-31|format=PDF}}</ref> He was listed as one of Australia's Smart 100 in a 2003 poll run by the Australian magazine [[The Bulletin]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://bulletin.ninemsn.com.au/bulletin/site/webAllArticles/93395FB0469ED912CA256DAF002C2CFC The | title = Bulletin Smart 100 | journal = [[The Bulletin]] | format = broken link | accessdate = 2006-06-25 }}</ref>

